column4: My ATV rolled over on me.
column5: Mr. Mazloum was brought to the office by a friend, following an accident with is ATV. Apparently, he and his friend were riding through some leaves, the ATV lost traction and rolled down a rather steep embankment. Mr. Mazloum was wearing jeans, boots, and a denim jacket at the time of the accident, but was not wearing a helmet. He was thrown from the vehicle, landing hard on his left arm, and the vehicle rolled over his right leg and ankle before continuing down the embankment. He says he had “the wind knocked out of me” by the fall but denies loss of consciousness, and his friend corroborates this. The friend tried to immobilize the leg before bringing Mr. Mazloum to the office, although his efforts were not successful. The patient says the pain in his arm at the moment is a 6 out of 10, his leg feels to be about 7 out of 10, and his ankle is about 9 out of 10.

column9: X-rays of the left elbow (2 views), right hip (2 views), and right ankle (2 views) were taken in house. Wet read revealed no fractures, but a moderate to severe right ankle sprain. Strapping was applied to the right ankle, and the patient was given crutches and instructed in their use. He is to remain non-weight-bearing for the next 48 hours. Advised to use ice on the ankle for the first 24 hours, then switch to heat for 24 hours. May use ibuprofen, 200 mg. q.i.d. for pain management. He is to remain off work until he is able to bear weight again. He is to return to the office in one week for a recheck. He is to call and come in sooner if his pain does not lessen within 24 hours, if there is additional swelling, or if there are any neurological complications. Patient and his friend were counseled regarding delayed symptoms of head injury and advised to go to the emergency department should Mr. Mazloum manifest any of these symptoms.

column4: I think I have a problem with my stomach.
column5:
Diane is in today complaining of a burning, gnawing sensation in her stomach which has been present for the past month or so. She also has episodes of intense heartburn about 15 to 20 minutes after eating, with an uncomfortable feeling of fullness. She has taken over-the-counter antacids with minimal relief. She has had two episodes of nausea and vomiting and she finds that when the pain is at its most intense, she gets some relief by drawing her knees up to her chest. The symptoms have worsened over the past two weeks to the point that she was unable to work for two days last week because of the pain, the nausea, and the vomiting.
Past medical history: Patient states she has generally felt well all of her life. She has had no hospitalizations. Her immunization record is complete. She reports an occasional cold in the winter, but no serious illnesses to date.
Social history: She is married and lives with her husband. They have no children. She works as a reporter at the Jefferson Times and says she enjoys her work. She smokes approximately 1 to 1 ½ packs of cigarettes daily, and has a glass of wine with dinner. She does not follow any particular diet, but says her eating habits are sporadic due to the nature of her work. She does not have an exercise routine, although she and her husband will occasionally go water skiing in the summer.

column7: Description of procedure: Procedure was explained to the patient and informed consent obtained. Patient was placed in left lateral position and the target site identified with ultrasound, which confirmed the presence of a 3.7 x 3 cm cyst in the upper medial renal capsule. The area was marked with a surgical pen, then prepped and draped in the usual sterile fashion. Xylocaine 1% was injected over the target. After adequate anesthesia, 20 mL of clear, reddish fluid was obtained and sent to the laboratory for analysis. Patient tolerated the procedure well; vital signs remained stable throughout the procedure.

column4: My wife is worried about my blood pressure.

Because of the readings, his wife encouraged him to seek treatment.

Stressed the importance of completing the course of medication, even if he begins to feel better. He is to remain at home until afebrile for 24 hours, rest, and drink plenty of fluids. He may continue to take ibuprofen for fever, and he is to call the office if his symptoms fail to resolve or worsen.
